# T2Lead Execution Safety

- Always use the  conda environment for project commands (never rely on `base`), preferably via `conda run -n <env_name> ...`.
- For Python/package commands, verify interpreter context first (`python -V` and environment identity) before long runs.
- For jobs expected to run longer than 10 minutes, use resilient launch by default (`tmux`/`screen`/`nohup`) unless the user explicitly requests foreground mode.
- For very large variant sets (for example >1000 variants), run a quick smoke subset first, then execute in chunks/batches for recoverability.
- For biomedical/pharma pipeline tasks, prioritize correctness and safety over speed:
  - do not claim success without evidence,
  - distinguish observed facts from hypotheses,
  - call out uncertainty explicitly.
- After code changes, run relevant tests or smoke checks before declaring done.
- For each run, create/update run records under `docs/experiments/runs/<date>_<run-name>_<run-id>/` with `REPORT.md`, `ARTIFACTS.md`, `COMMANDS.md`, and `METADATA.yaml`.
- In `docs/`, default to Chinese for internal reports unless the user asks for bilingual or English collaboration copies.
- Work in small increments: after each small implementation step, run relevant tests before moving on.
- After each meaningful change, check `git status` and `git diff` to verify scope.
- Do not claim completion without test/log evidence.
- If a run fails/is interrupted, report:
  - last confirmed successful step,
  - last log timestamp,
  - likely causes with confidence level,
  - recovery plan.
